SEMANTIC PRINCIPLE (universal, apply to ALL objects, not just events):
- Verb CREATE/SET/WRITE/DELETE an entity (destructive/mutating action)
  → maps to the operational verb (create/set/write/delete/move/send/share).
  Examples: «schedule appointment» = create events, «send email» = send messages,
  «delete file» = delete files, «create folder» = create dirs, «share
  the sheet with Y» = share files (ADR 0128 outbound consent).
- Verb ASK/PROPOSE/SUGGEST/SHOW (inquiry action, read-only) → read.
  The text summary of the result occurs in the planner's final_answer;
  there is NO dedicated describe_<object> executor for most
  objects (exception: describe_numbers for pure numeric lists
  statistical compute). Examples: «propose 3 times» = read events, «show me
  X's files» = read files, «which N are free?» = read events.
- If the sentence mixes both senses («if there is space book the appointment»)
  the winning intent is the MUTATING VERB (create for events post ADR 0128) —
  the check_availability is handled at the planner level as a pre-action
  (read_events).
NOTE ON events vs proposals:
- events = APPOINTMENTS / MEETINGS / ENGAGEMENTS of the calendar (agenda).
  "schedule/book/schedule/create appointment|meeting|gathering|meeting" = create events (ADR 0128).
- proposals = INTERNAL PROPOSALS of Metnos' synth/introvertive system
  (suggestions to improve the catalog itself). Never user-facing intent.
  If the query talks about "appointment/meeting/gathering/meeting" it is NOT proposals.
SINGLE vs CONTAINER RULE:
When the query distinguishes between a SINGLE element and a CONTAINER (folder,
group, set), the object is the container if the action treats the container
as a unit (sum/count/sort PER container, work ON THE
container), otherwise it is the element.
- Action on the element (reading, criterion, hash, rendering of content,
  modification of the single item): object = element (files, messages, lines, ...).
- Action on the container (popularity, aggregated size, tree
  structure, top containers, creation/deletion of the container itself):
  object = container (dirs, ...).
"find .py files" → files (criterion on singles).
"find the largest directories" → dirs (on containers).
"count totals aggregating by folder" → dirs (aggregate on container).
"total size of the path" → dirs (on the container).
"structure of subdirectories" → dirs (on the container).
"create the folder" → dirs (action on the container itself).

COMPOUND (MORE ACTIONS IN SEQUENCE):
If the request contains MORE actions in sequence (typical: "do X and then Y",
"find ... and write ...", "take ... and put them ...", "download ... and send ..."),
respond with a JSON ARRAY of {verb,object} objects, ONE per action, IN THE ORDER
of execution. Each clause carries ITS REAL object (the object on which THAT
action acts), NEVER a single global object repeated. Single action → a single
JSON object, not an array.
Compound examples:
"find processes using most memory and write a report" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"processes"},{"verb":"write","object":"files"}]
"read closed issues and put them in a spreadsheet" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"issues"},{"verb":"create","object":"files"}]
"download invoices from the site and send them to me by email" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"urls"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]
"find photos from 2020, compress them and send them to me" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"files"},{"verb":"compress","object":"files"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]

Respond ONLY with the JSON, no prose.

